{{Infobox protected area | name = Dark Canyon Wilderness | iucn_category = Ib | photo = Dark Canyon Wilderness.jpg | photo_caption = | map = USA | relief = 1 | coords = {{coord|37.7763793|-109.8976330|format=dms|region:US-UT_source:gnis|display=inline,title}} <ref>[https://geonames.usgs.gov/apex/f?p=gnispq:3:::NO::P3_FID:2035101 GNIS: Feature Detail Report for: Dark Canyon Wilderness ]</ref> | location = [[San Juan County, Utah|San Juan County]], [[Utah]], [[United States|USA]] | nearest_city = [[Monticello, Utah]] | area = {{convert|47116|acres}} | established = September 18, 1984 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = [[United States Forest Service|U.S. Forest Service]] }}
[[Image:Dark Canyon Ruin.jpg|thumb|292px|right|Ancestral Puebloan ruin in Dark Canyon Wilderness]]
'''Dark Canyon Wilderness''' is a [[National Wilderness Preservation System|designated Wilderness Area]] in the heart of southeast [[Utah]]'s canyon country, part of the [[Bears Ears National Monument]]. The wilderness is named for its high steep walls that narrow in the lower section so that they block the light in the morning and late afternoon. The roughly horseshoe-shaped [[wilderness]] is made up of the upper part of {{convert|40|mi|0|adj=on}} long Dark Canyon and two major tributaries, Woodenshoe Canyon and Peavine Canyon in the [[Manti-La Sal National Forest]]. These canyons all descend from pine-covered Elk Ridge northeast of [[Natural Bridges National Monument]]. Dark Canyon continues west within a U.S. [[Bureau of Land Management]] primitive area that is recommended for wilderness designation. The last four miles of the main canyon drop steeply through [[Glen Canyon National Recreation Area]] into [[Lake Powell]].
On December 28, 2016 President [[Barack Obama]] proclaimed the 1.35 million acre [[Bears Ears National Monument]], that includes both the Dark Canyon Wilderness and the adjacent Dark Canyon Primitive Area.
Life zones range from [[ponderosa pine]] and [[aspen]]-covered high country to desert vegetation in the bottom of Dark Canyon. High terraced castle-like [[sandstone]] walls tower {{convert|3000|ft|sigfig=2}} above the canyon floors. Wildlife species include [[mule deer]], some [[Cougar|mountain lions]], [[American black bear|black bear]] and [[bighorn sheep]]. This diverse canyon country contains [[natural arch|arches]], springs, seeps and hanging gardens.
Water sources in Dark Canyon are often widely separated, and some have dried up entirely in recent drought years. Thunderstorms can result in powerful [[flash flood]]s that scour the canyon streambeds.
Wilderness visitors may see evidence of the [[Ancient Pueblo Peoples|Ancestral Puebloan]] culture.
All the trails dropping into the canyons are moderate but they can be difficult, if not impossible, to find and follow until you reach the bottoms of the canyons. Peavine Canyon contains a cherry-stem jeep trail. The [[U.S. Forest Service|Forest Service]] once recommended closing the area to vehicles but this corridor was kept open as a compromise in the [[Utah Wilderness Act of 1984]].
